<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910425-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>910425-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Publicker Industries Cleanup</HL><DATE>04/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   PUL</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)</RE><LP>   OLD GREENWICH, Conn. -- Publicker Industries Inc. said theestimated cost of cleanup activities at one of its facilitieswas reduced to $14 million from $22 million by the federalgovernment.   As previously reported, the Environmental ProtectionAgency filed suit against the company and two other partiesto recover expenses incurred by the EPA in its cleanup of theformer Publicker storage facility in Philadelphia. At thetime, EPA had said it spent more than $22 million under thefederal Superfund Act that covers cleanup of hazardous wastesites.</LP><TEXT>   The company has said it still doesn't know the full extentof its liability, but has noted that if it was determined tobe liable for any &quot;significant portion&quot; of the amounts soughtby the U.S., it could have a &quot;material adverse effect&quot; on thefinancial condition of the alcohol and chemical company.</TEXT></DOC>